flowchart TD
    A([Change Request]) --> B{Emergency?}
    B --> |Yes| C[Emergency CAB]
    B --> |No| D[Standard Review]
    C --> E[Expedited Approval]
    D --> F[Weekly CAB Meeting]
    F --> G{Approved?}
    G --> |Yes| H[Schedule Change Window]
    G --> |No| I[Return to Requester]
    H --> J[Implementation]
    J --> K{Successful?}
    K --> |Yes| L[Post-Impl Review]
    %% ⚡ CHANGED SECTION
    K --> |No| M1[Execute Backout Plan]
    M1 --> M2{Backout Successful?}
    M2 --> |Yes| M3[Document Backout & Reschedule]
    M2 --> |No| M[Incident Report]
    M3 --> N
    %% ⚡ END CHANGED SECTION
    L --> N([Close Change])
    M --> N

%% ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
%% CLAUDE'S CHANGE INTERPRETATION
%% ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
%% OBJECTIVE: Ensure failed implementations follow a structured rollback procedure before escalating to incident management, minimizing service disruption during change windows.
%%
%% EXPLANATION:
%% Replaced the direct link from failed implementation to Incident Report with a backout plan flow: when implementation fails, an "Execute Backout Plan" step is triggered first, followed by a decision node checking if the backout was successful. If the backout succeeds, the change is documented and rescheduled for a future window. If the backout also fails, it then escalates to an Incident Report, preserving the original escalation path for worst-case scenarios.
%% ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
